./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/quinte_essence_converted.xml	s100	and þe oolde feble man schal vse þis deuyn drynk at morn and at euen  ech tyme a walnoteschelle fulle and wiþinne a fewe dayes he schal so hool þat he schal fele him silf of þe statt and þe strenkþe of 3eer  and he schal haue greet ioie þat he is come to þe statt of 3ongþe  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/quinte_essence_converted.xml	s104	and þanne 3e schal se him rise vp and speke  and wondirfully be comfortid and strenkþid þerby þanne comforte him wiþ ministracioun of oure quinte essencie afore seid  and he schal be al hool but if it be so þat god wole algatis þat he schal die And I seie to 3ou truly  þat þis is þe hi3este maistrie þat may be in transmutacioun of kynde  for ri3t fewe lechis now lyuynge knowe þis priuytee  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/quinte_essence_converted.xml	s105	The þridde medicyn is to cure þe lepre þat is causid of corrupcioun and putrifaccioun of ony of þe principal humouris of man  but not þe lepre þat comeþ to man of kynde of þe fadir and of þe modir leprous   for it is callid morbus hereditus   ne þe lepre þat is sent of god by his plage  but þat þat is causid oonly of rotun humouris take oure essence aforeseid  wiþ þe quinte essence of goold and peerl  a litil quantite at oonys  and vse it in maner as I seide afore and wiþinne a fewe daies he schal be partily hool þerof  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/quinte_essence_converted.xml	s106	and if 3e haue non preparate redy oure essence  þanne take in þe stide þerof fyn brennynge watir but þat oþer is bettere  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/quinte_essence_converted.xml	s110	Forsoþe alle philosophoris seyn þat þe palesye vniuersel comeþ of haboundaunce of viscous humouris closynge þe metis of vertu animale  sensityue  and motyue  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/quinte_essence_converted.xml	s111	And þerfore it is necessarie þat þo þingis þat schal cure þis sijknes be temperate  hoot  and moist  and a litil attractyue  and to þe synous confortatyue Therfore  blessid be god  makere of kynde  þat ordeynede for þe man paralitike oure essence aforseid  þat souereynly to him comfortynge  restorynge  and temperatly worchynge þerfore fixe þerinne þe essence of þo laxatyues þat purgen flewme  viscous humouris  as a litil of euforbie  or turbit  or sambucy  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/quinte_essence_converted.xml	s112	 þanne wiþoute doute  if god wole  þe paralitik man schal be hool wiþ comfortynge and restorynge of kynde  if 3e make him a stewe hoot and moist with herbis  þat is to seye  eerbe yue   sauge  þat haue an heuenly strenkþe to comforte þe joynctis   þe senewis  and þe vertu motyue

./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/quinte_essence_converted.xml	s119	certeyn experience techiþ þat colerik men 3eueþ to summe ymagynaciouns  and sangueyn men ben ocupied aboute summe oþere ymagynaciouns   3itt flewmatik men aboute oþere but þo men þat habounde in blak coler  þat is  malencoly  ben occupied a þousand part wiþ mo þou3tis þan ben men of ony oþer complexioun Forwhi  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/quinte_essence_converted.xml	s120	þat humour of blak coler is so noyous  þat if it abounde and asende vp to þe heed  it troubliþ alle þe my3tis of þe brayn  engendrynge noyous ymagynaciouns  bryngynge yn horrible þou3tis boþe wakynge and slepinge  and siche maner of men ben born vndir þe constillacioun of saturne  the wickide planete Forsoþe  to siche men deuelis wole gladly appere   minister to hem her priuy temptaciouns wiþinne þe cours of her þou3tis  and þese men þus turmentid wiþ þe passiouns of malencoly comounly speke wiþ hem  stryue and dispute wiþ hem silf whanne þei be aloone  þat ofte tymes oþere folk may heere it These maner of men þat ben þus turmentid  as weel by passioun of malencoly as of deuelis  ofte tymes falle in dispeir  and at þe laste sle hem silf þe perfi3t cure of alle þese is oure essencie auri et perelarum  or ellis brennynge watir in stide þerof  in þe whiche 3e fixe gold as it is aforeseid  wherinne be putt a litil of sen~e~ or watir of fumiter  or poudre of lapis lasuly  or ellis medullam ebuli  and vse it discreetly

./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/quinte_essence_converted.xml	s129	forsoþe in alle siche placis þei wole abide and schewe hem to her foloweris but forsoþe þo þingis þat ben of þe nature of Iubiter and of sol  goode planetis  arne displesynge to him  and contrarie  and naturaly deuelis fle awey fro hem  for þei haue greet abhominacioun of þer vertuous influence þerfore it schewiþ weel þat þo þingis þat ben in þis world  summe þer ben þat bitokene þe glorious yoie of heuene  and summe þing þat figure þe derknesse of euerlastynge peynes of helle Forsoþe þe sunne and iubiter  goode planetis   gold  pure metal  and alle pure þingis þat gladen a man  figurynge by resoun þe ioie of heuene and blak Saturne  and þe spotty moone  figure  bitokene þe condicioun of helle and siþ þat deuelis be dampned   ful of wreche of helle  þerfore þei hate þe clennesse  þe ioie of oure lord god  of hise seyntis also þei haten þe sunne and his cleernes  and pure þingis þat maken a man glad  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/quinte_essence_converted.xml	s130	and naturaly it plesiþ hem to dwelle in derk   in blak  orrible  stynkynge placis  in heuynesse  wreche   malencoly   in þo þingis þat pretende þe condicioun of helle And siþ oure  essence aforeseid is so heuenly a þing   by sotil craft brou3t to so myche swetnes  it is so souereyn a medicyn þat it may weel be lijkned to þe ioie of paradice

./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/quinte_essence_converted.xml	s146	The medicyn to heele þe feuere contynuele  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/quinte_essence_converted.xml	s147	alle philosophoris seyn þat þe feuere contynuele is gendrid of putrifaccioun of blood and of corrupcieun of humouris in it þerfore þe cure þerof is to purge blood  and to putte awey þe corrupcioun of it   þe humoris vneuene to make euene  þe nature lost to restore  and so restorid to kepe Forsoþe alle þese þingis worcheþ oure quinte essence  and þerfore it curiþ perfi3tly þe feuere contynuele and þou3 brennynge watir caste out fro blood watry humouris and corrupt  3itt take it nou3t in þis cure forwhi  þou3 brennynge watir be tymes distillid  3itt it is not fully depurid fro his brennynge heete   þe elementis but siþ oure  essence is not hoot  ne moist  coold  ne drie  as ben þe  elementis þerfore it heeliþ perfi3tly þe contynuel feuere  namely wiþ commixtioun of þe essence of gold  peerle and if 3e wole strenkþe 3oure medicyn  þanne putte yn oure  essence a litil quantite of pulpa cassie fistule or ellis þe iuys of þe eerbe mercuriale  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/quinte_essence_converted.xml	s150	and þe pacient schal be hool wiþoute doute  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/quinte_essence_converted.xml	s153	haþ strenkþe and vertu to consume þe rotun watery inordinat  and to myche coold humidite þerfore take oure essence or brennynge watir  and putte þerinne a litil of euforbij  turbit  or sambuci  or sum oþir þing þat purgiþ flewme  and vse it morowe and eue   þe pacient schal be hool  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/quinte_essence_converted.xml	s154	The medicyn for to cure þe feuere agu  and þe lunatik man and womman discreet maistris seyn  þat þe feuere agu comounly is causid of a uyolent reed coler adust  and of blood adust  and of blak coler adust  and sumtyme of oon of þese adust  and sumtyme of two togidere  and sumtyme of togidere and þerfore þe feuere agu is þe posityue degree  and in þe superlatyue degree  comparatif gree  superlatif gree For þe feuere agu haþ comounly alienacioun of witt   schewynge of þingis of fantasy And 3e schal knowe weel whiche ben þe humouris adust þat causen þe feuere  be þese tokenes Forwhi  if þe pacient seiþ þat he seeþ blak þingis  þanne blak coler  þat is  malencolie  is adust  if he se þingis of gold reed coler is adust if reed þingis  and schewynge of bloodt þanne blood is adust And if he seiþ þat he seeþ alle þese iij  þingis  þanne alle þe humouris ben adust For as myche as brennynge watir ascendiþ to þe heed  and gladly wole a man drynke And siþ þat feuere agu regneþ in þe regioun of þe heed þe philosophoris counceilis þat þe pacient schal not resceyue it in þis sijknes but it is nedeful þat he take oure essence of gold and of peerl  meynging þe part of essence of watir of rose  violet  borage  and letuse and þanne 3e schulen haue an heuenly medicyn to cure perfi3tly þis sijknesse

./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/quinte_essence_converted.xml	s172	and þerinne putte a litil of aloes epatik  euforbij   a litil of ierapigra galieni  of essence  of þe rote of lilie and also of gold  peerle  capilli veneris and ysope  for þese þingis ben nedeful to siche feueris  apostemes it is nedeful also þat wiþ þese þingis þer be sich a quinta essencia laxatyue þat wole purge þe superflue humouris þat abounde  and þat þe pacient so myche resceyue in a natural day þerof þat he may go weel oonys to sege  and so lete him vse þis laxatif in þe woke  But be weel war þat he take wiþ oure quinta essencia but ri3t a litil quantite of þe laxatif at oonys  as I tolde 3ou tofore  for peril þat mi3te bifalle

./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sekenesse_of_wymmen_2_converted.xml	s81	If it be of blode  þen þer ys mych pryching þer as þe mater of þe posteme ys gedurd to gedre and þey hafe comynly a contynualle feuer but not ful stronge  and þe veynes of hir legges be swollon  hyr vryn ys clere reed  oþer whiles dym red  and maner swart yeloo a boue vndur þe serkull

./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s9	God made blood of water right And þe body of þe erthe dight  And al þe water into erthe sinketh  And al þe erthe þe water drinketh For to maintene al þinge Þat waxeþ in the erthe springinge  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s11	And whanne þe soule departe shal  He bereþ the blood wiþ him al  And whanne þe hete is from him went  Þe blood is into water sent  And þanne þe body þat is drye And rype may not longe lye Þat it ne drinkeþ þe blood also As þe erthe þe water do   
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s13	Off þe kinde of þe erthe  it is tolde  And al his complexioun is colde  For he is made  withouten les  Of the elementes  For of þe erthe is þe fleisshe And of þe water his blood neisshe  Of þe eyr his soule made was And of þe fire þe hete he has

./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s25	And in þat time þe childe is bore As a sykenesse of deeþ bi ware  But as sone as þe body bare Haþ sauered þe eir þat is here And þe feble bones gynneþ stere  Þanne þei bigynne to drie anoon And wexen hard and fallen to boon  And alle þe ioyntes þat weren open In þe womman a3ein ben cropen  Herken and I shal telle þe howh  If a man his finger drowh  Þe ioynte wole open and vndo And siþen crepe a3ein þerto  So fareþ wymmen after childing Þorgh þe grace of heuene king   
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s28	If hoote of kinde be þe womman And greet liking haþ to man  Oon chaumbre or two or thre Of þilke þat in hir matrice be Of greet wille open þera3ein Whan þat a man haþ by hir lein  þe seed falleþ in hem anon And þei closen a3ein echon And if þat seed acordaunce finde  It wexeþ ferþer in his kinde  And if þat þe oþere chaumbres be Open and it be so þat she Knowe a man ofte þat same night Or on þe morwe bi þe daylight Or þe secounde day  latter noght  And þe seed be þerynne broght  Þei closen and holden faste And children norisshen at þe laste  And so longe þei shullen be vnbore As þe seed of oþer weren sowe bifore As þei weren geten wonderly  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s34	And if þei togidre at þe bygynnyng Be liþe and glade in all þing  Of glade semblant þe childe schal be As þei were boþe at þe semble  And if þei assemble hem wroþely The childe schal be such  sikerly  And if þat oon ben glad and þat oþer nou3t And a childe bitwene hem wrou3t  Þe childe shal be somtime bliþe And somtime greet felnesse kiþe  And if þat it bifalle so Þat þe oone of hem two Haue any man gretly in þoght Whanne þe seed is to his chaumbre broght  Þat seed may take liknesse  percas  Of him þat her þoght in was   
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s35	Hardinesse of man and drede  Wherof come þei  so God þe spede   
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s37	Þou woost wel þat men made were Of þe foure ellement3 that ere And þerto God 3aue him goost  And aftir a man haþ in him moost  Of weet or drie  hete or colde  His complexioun shal be tolde  And if þise euene be Delid in man  þanne shal he Be noþer coward ne hardy  Listen  and I shal telle þe why  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s38	If colde ouercome not þe hete Ne þe drie ouercome not þe wete So þat þe hete  colde  weet  and drye In the herte of man euene lie  For þe euenhede of hem þo Stire it shal neiþer to ne fro  And if þe hete þe colde ouergo And þe drie þe weet also  Þe body begynneþ for to quake And þe herte to stere and shake And for þe hete he is hardy anoon And dredeþ not he lokeþ vpon  And if þe colde be maister ouere þe hete And ouer þe drie also þe wete  Þe body wexeþ colde at nede And þe herte neisshe and ful of drede   
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s40	Miselrie and scalle also Of þe womman come boþe two

./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s46	Þe erþe sustineth and taketh  Þe eir norissheþ it and maketh  Þe watir it fediþ and makiþ it grene  And þe hete of þe sunne doiþ it sustene  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s50	Oone is þorgh kynde  As clerkes in her bokes fynde  For if þe man broun be And þe wijf as wel as he And þei togidre haue engendrure  It oght to be broun of nature  And if þat oon be broun and þat oþer white And þei assemble wiþ grete delite  Whos seed of moost delite festneþ When it in þe chaumbre resteþ  Of þat side shal þe child be Most yliche of shap and ble  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s54	Wicked humers makeþ malencolie And þat engendreþ felonye  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s55	Þe wicked humours ben kyndly smert And gloweþ somwhile aboute þe hert And enchafeþ it as fire And makeþ it derke and blak for ire  And þat merknesse answeriþ þenne Vp into þe herne panne  And when þe hernes beþ imerked so  A greet dele of witte þei done forgo And smyteþ anoon in felonye And þat makeþ þe herte so drye  But whan þe humours done sees And of her glowinges ben in pees  Þe herte restith and stille lendith And þe merkenesse fro him wendith  And þe lemes lightne euerichone And in good pointe bicomeþ anone   
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s56	Þei þat eten and drinken more þan nede is  Wheþer done þei  wel or amis   
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s59	A man þat eteth at a mele Til him þinke þat he is wele And leith sone aboue more Or þat be defied bifore  His stomak encombreþ he And þe hete þat þerynne shulde be  And so his kinde he bringeþ doun And himself to corrupcioun  And his witt in þat is lesse Þan a beest þat etith gresse  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s60	For þer is neiþer hors ne cow Þat  whanne he haþ ete inow  Þat wole ete any more Til efte þat him hungred sore  And siþen þat a beest dooþ þus  More shulde a man þat feleþ his pous Distempred and is not wel at ese Ete mesurably  his God to plese  For þei þat han her resoun and witt Han þe miche more nede to gouerne it  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s61	Þerfore  I seie  amys þei do Þat etith more þanne mister is to  Ouþer drinke  wheþer it be  I rede þou lerne wel þis of me   
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s62	Wheþer 3eueþ a man more kunnyng  Hoote mete or colde in eting   
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s63	 A man þat vsith hote metis  It enchawfeþ him whan he etis  The synewis norisshiþ he þerby And alle þe veynes of his body  It warmeþ the brayne and þe herte And of wittes makeþ hem smerte  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s64	Coolde metis doth noght þerto But keleþ synwes and veynes also And steriþ the humours most to ille Þat hote metes wolde kepe stille In good temperure wel and fyn And from yuel make it declyn  For whan a man fediþ his body And eteþ colde mete gredily  It keleþ þe brayn and þe herte And þe witt it makeþ derke  And whan þe wittes ben so keled  Þe lesse kunnynge þei haue feled   
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s65	 A man þat is in hele and 3ing  Hou wraþþeth he him for litel þing   
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s66	 I shal þe seie hou and why  Þe herte is lord of þe body And þe body is his wardayn And his seruaunt wiþ al his mayn For al þat likeþ þe herte to It liketh to þe body also  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s67	Þe men beth gouernours of þe herte And þe eeren messageris smerte  Þe tunge avokett is she And þe sighte his sonde be  Þe hondis beeþ hise knightes two  Þe hertes castel is heed þerto  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s68	If þe herte heere a worde  Be it yuel  be it goode  He may it not wite ne knowe But his messangere it him showe  And if þat þe erande him like  He reioyseþ him wonderlike And alle þe membris haue ioye and blis Of þat þe herte so ioyful is  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s69	But whan þe messageris tellen him to Anyþing þat is yuel do  He steriþ and quakeþ wrothfully And alle hise membres ben sory And alle þei ben wrooþ and quake also As þei knowen himself do  Hise enemyes ben bliþe þerfore And on hise membres ben glowyinge sore  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s72	And hise men ben as feble as he And þoleþ not her aduersite But to misdo þei stere hem smerte And al þe scathe betideþ the herte For þe body may take no scathe But if þe herte fele it rathe   
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s74	Off flewmes þat in þe body renne Comeþ fathed  whoso hem kenne  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s75	And if þe flewmes be swete  Þorgh þe body sone þei shete And þe hete of othir þing Sle þei and hemself spring And lordshipe þei haue anoon Ouer þe humours euerichon  And whan þat þei lord are  Þe swetnesse of hem torneþ 3are Into grese  þanne gadreþ þat And maketh so the body fat  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s76	And if þe flewmes be salte wiþynne  Þe flesshe and þe body þei brenne And felowred anon þei take Into colours 3elowe and blake  And whanne þei in lymes and veines sprede And þe colours wiþ hem lede  So longe as þei þeryn dure Þei reuen þe body of norture And holdeþ it so lene alway Þat it no greece gadre may  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s79	 A man is made  as þou haste herde  Of þinges in þis midlerde  Of fire and water  erthe and ayr  Boþe þe foule and eke þe fair  And þese foure echone be Contrarie to oþer in qualite  And þe body may not blynne Þere þese foure ben gadred ynne But togidre haue bataille Euere til some of hem faille  And whanne þat oone to noght is broght  Þe toþer no lenger lyue may noght  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s81	Þan may no power ne ricchesse No kunynge ne doghtinesse Ne noon excusacioun may he make Whanne þat deeþ comeþ and wole him take  For good folk  wickid  and shrewis  3onge and olde and pouere of good þewes  Þe riche and stronge  mowen not faille  Þe feble  fooles  ne þe wise  saunzfaile  Greet ne smal  shal noon of þise For no mede ne none emprise Ascape þe deeþ  þat he ne mote goo To þe erthe þere he come fro

./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s94	And if a womman conseiue ne might  And she þat oignement toke aright Wiþ good wille and putte it sotilly In þe priuete of hir body And bere it þere daies thre So þat euery day it chaunged be And þe ferþe night her spedde Wiþ hir housbonde to goo to bedde  Anoon she shulde conceiue þere But if þe boþe barein were

./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s99	Þis oignement is made also Of diuerse herbis þat gooþ þerto  Þe preciousest þat men may finde In al þe londe of Greet Ynde  Þre hundrid fourti and twoo Goth to þe making and no moo  And white dragouns grece þerto shal be And þat men finde in yles of þe see  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s100	And ouer a fire it shal dwelle In þe makyng forto welle daies or seuene  As þei finde by þe cours of heuene And by þe art of astronomye And after þe signes lowe or hye  And þe fire þerevnder al Of þe herbe rootes dight be shal And þe herbes þat it is of dight Ben kept ful honestly  I þe plight  Þat vnneþe dar þei any of hem take Whanne þat oignement he shal make

./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s115	Feblenesse of reines is þe þridde  As whan a womman is so bitidde  Some womman wiþ childe may be And feble of reynes eke may be she Þat she is not of þe might Þe peine of childinge to suffre right  Þe modir steriþ hir and turneþ aboute So þat þe childe falleþ oute Of þe chaumbre þat lieth ynne  Wiþ greet peyne þei parte atwynne  Whan it is out  þanne is it lorne Whan it is þan so deed borne  And þorgh grace of Goddes might Þe modir closiþ anoon right

./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s121	Of suche condicioun some ben  lo  And þat may be þorgh þinges þre Þat many wymmen wiþ endowed be  Oone is if she be faire and white  For a man haþ more delite In hir þat is bright of ble Þan in a loþely for to se  Anoþer skile is noble wede  For a man had leuere 3eue mede To hir þat is clenly dight Þan to a pouere ragged wight  Þe þridde skile þat whan a man So grete loue haþ to a womman Þat him þinkeþ none so swete to holde  For  Loue haþ no lak   as seiþ þe olde

./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/sidrak_and_bokkus_converted.xml	s188	And eueriche haþ his powere In diuerse quarters of þe 3ere  Capricorne  Aquarie  and Pisses  Þre þinges þe firste quarter ches  And of flewmes haue þei mighte And wete and colde is her righte  In Decembre þei begynne And in þe midle of Mars þei blynne  Þat is þe coldeste time of alle For þat is þat we winter calle

./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/trevisa_on_the_properties_of_things_2_converted.xml	s14	Þe firste tweyne ben principallich iclepid actiue  no3t for þey worchin alone  for þe passiue qualites worchiþ also for non qualite is in þe body an ydel  but þerfore þey beþ iclepid actiue for be þe worchinge of hem þe oþir beþ ibrou3t inne and ikept and isaued  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/trevisa_on_the_properties_of_things_2_converted.xml	s16	Þe hete of þe salt dissolueþ þe parties þat beþ erþy and watry and aiery  and so slakinge and neisschinge þe hete bringiþ in moistnes  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/trevisa_on_the_properties_of_things_2_converted.xml	s17	Hete bringiþ in drynesse  for hete worchinge in moistnesse dissolueþ it first and þan he distroieþ it  and þan comeþ in drines  þat is þe file of þe hete  and is also ikept  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/trevisa_on_the_properties_of_things_2_converted.xml	s19	While hete worchiþ in a þing  first he deleþ þe parties þerof and þan þe þing is feblere þat was strengere be þe ioynynge togedres of þe parties  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/trevisa_on_the_properties_of_things_2_converted.xml	s20	Þerfore he wiþstondiþ þe lasse þe worchinge of þat þing þat worchiþ  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/trevisa_on_the_properties_of_things_2_converted.xml	s22	And þis hete gendriþ and saueþ  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/trevisa_on_the_properties_of_things_2_converted.xml	s23	And þerfore frogges somtyme ben igendrid in þe aier be þe hete of heuen  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/trevisa_on_the_properties_of_things_2_converted.xml	s25	And þe hete corrumpiþ and distroieþ  as whan þe bemes of li3t comeþ togedres in a certein point of a clere body  an 3if þe bemes were ioyned in a myrour þan me my3te tende and brenne hurdenne be þe reboundinge of þe bemes  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/trevisa_on_the_properties_of_things_2_converted.xml	s26	And also he bringeþ and lediþ þe neþir þinges to þe ouere  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/trevisa_on_the_properties_of_things_2_converted.xml	s28	And so he bringiþ þe neþir and þe middel into þe ouere  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/trevisa_on_the_properties_of_things_2_converted.xml	s29	Also he naisschiþ þingis þat beþ harde  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/trevisa_on_the_properties_of_things_2_converted.xml	s31	Also nessche þinges and fletinge he makþ harde  as it is sene in an ey þat is irostid  for þe licour and moistoure and sotil parties wastiþ awey and þe erþy parties abidiþ and so þe ey wexiþ hard  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/trevisa_on_the_properties_of_things_2_converted.xml	s33	While it meueþ from þe middel to þe vtmest parties  by his strengþe he dissolueþ and todeleþ þing þat he worchiþ inne and makeþ it couenable to his worchinge  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/trevisa_on_the_properties_of_things_2_converted.xml	s37	3if it be fine golde  he meltiþ it be strengþe of hete and destroyeþ it no3t  for fyne golde  þou3 he melte wiþ hete  he lesiþ no3t of þe wi3te  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/trevisa_on_the_properties_of_things_2_converted.xml	s38	Also oþirwhile hete distroyeþ  as it happiþ whan he deleþ more þan he wastiþ  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/trevisa_on_the_properties_of_things_2_converted.xml	s39	Þan þe humour roteþ and is corrupt  as it fareþ in wete hupel of whete  þe hete iclosid þerinne dissolueþ and todeliþ þe watir into smoke  and þe smoke iholde and iclosid þerinne nesscheþ þe greynes and makeþ rotye and corrumpiþ hem  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/trevisa_on_the_properties_of_things_2_converted.xml	s40	And hete kindeliche makeþ of heuy þinges li3te  for whanne mosture is iwastid be hete þe wi3te is þe lasse and þing is þe more li3t  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/trevisa_on_the_properties_of_things_2_converted.xml	s42	And herfore it is þat bodies of bestis þat ben quyk ben li3ter þan þe bodies of bestis þat ben dede for þe hete and þe spirit þat is conteined in arteries and veynes  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/trevisa_on_the_properties_of_things_2_converted.xml	s44	But somtyme it happiþ þat with worchinge hete makeþ þinges heuy  and worchiþ in a þing and wastiþ þe moistfulle parties and li3t  and þe boistous and heuy parties abidiþ  and þan þe þing is þe more sadfast and compact and so þe more heuy  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/trevisa_on_the_properties_of_things_2_converted.xml	s45	Also by openynge of smale holes and poores by strengþe of þe hete  þe spiritis bene idrawe out  and by presens of hem þe body is þe li3tere an bi absens of hem þe body is þe more heuy  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/trevisa_on_the_properties_of_things_2_converted.xml	s47	And þanne fury parties biclippiþ þe vtmost parties of þe þing and 3eueþ it a liknes  and so firy colour  þat is  reed  is gendrid  as it is isene in roses

./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/trevisa_on_the_properties_of_things_2_converted.xml	s52	For 3if it worchiþ at þe vttermest in a þing  at þe laste it todeliþ it and distroieþ at þe ende  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/trevisa_on_the_properties_of_things_2_converted.xml	s53	And oþirwhile it saueþ þe lif

./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/trevisa_on_the_properties_of_things_2_converted.xml	s55	Þanne of þis þat is iseide gedre þou þat hete is an element propirte  most abil to worche  most perischinge  most meuable to meue  igendrid of þe meuynge of bemes  and multiplieþ itsilf and comeþ to oþir and chaungiþ into his owne liknes þingis þat he worchiþ inne  and 3eueþ lif to þinges þat ben dede and distroyed with coolde and renewiþ hem  as it is isene in rootes and plantis þat dyeþ in þe wintir coolde and lyueþ in þe hete in springinge tyme  
./data/MIDDLE-MODERN-ENGLISH-MEDICAL-CORPUS-Copy/01_MEMT_Texts/trevisa_on_the_properties_of_things_2_converted.xml	s56	Hete bringiþ þe neþir in þe ouere  and worchiþ and distroieþ superfluytees  and clensinge of filþe and hoore
